    thinking: "**Analyzing the Requirements**\n\nOkay, I\'m now laser-focused on the specifics of this request. The \"Culling Games\" central control panel from *Jujutsu Kaisen* is the primary target. However, the critical instruction about a SINGLE HTML file is absolutely paramount. I\'m prioritizing this constraint above all else.\n\n\n**Isolating Core Requirements**\n\nI\'ve got it. The absolute key is to bypass the provided React setup completely. My focus is now on constructing a solitary HTML file using only standard HTML5 tags and Tailwind CSS utility classes. The instruction to include the CDN script within the `<head>` to ensure immediate style rendering is also paramount. I\'m discarding any frontend framework code to meet the requirement.\n\n\n**Confirming Implementation Approach**\n\nOkay, the single static HTML page approach in `index.html` feels correct now. The key is using vanilla JS within the HTML, served directly by Vite. This eliminates any React dependency, perfectly satisfying the single-file constraint and ensuring seamless execution within our Cloud Run environment. Vite\'s ability to serve `index.html` as-is, without any module bundling, simplifies the setup. I\'m focusing on ensuring proper compilation and serving with Vite.\n\n\n**Refining Standalone Structure**\n\nI\'m now diving deeper into Vite\'s capabilities with plain HTML. While Vite *does* support plain HTML, my next steps involve ensuring this standalone HTML file can be fully independent. I\'m checking for and cleaning up any console errors. I\'ll also ensure `/src/main.tsx` is either safely removed or adapted, and I am exploring the `metadata.json` for name and description values.\n\n\n"
